6. Open Source

Free to use and supported by a large community.

Interview Answer (5–6 Lines)

Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that allows JavaScript to run outside the browser. JavaScript is a programming language, whereas Node.js is an environment used to execute JavaScript code. Node.js is mainly used for backend development, web servers, APIs, database connectivity, and real-time applications. Its main advantages are high performance, asynchronous processing, scalability, and a large npm package ecosystem.

2.) What are the features of Node.js and how does Node.js work in client-server architecture?

Interview-Friendly Explanation

"Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that allows us to run JavaScript outside the browser. Its main features are fast performance, asynchronous and non-blocking I/O, single-threaded architecture, event-driven programming, cross-platform support, and a large package ecosystem through NPM.

In client-server architecture, the client sends a request to the Node.js server. The server receives the request, processes it (and may interact with files or databases), then sends a response back to the client. Because Node.js uses a non-blocking and event-driven model, it can handle many client requests efficiently."

Node.js Uses a Non-Blocking and Event-Driven Model
1. Non-Blocking (Doesn't Wait)
Node.js does not wait for a task to finish.
It starts the task and moves on to other work.

2. Event-Driven (Works on Events)
Node.js listens for events.
When an event happens, it runs the related code.

Examples of Events:

User clicks a button.
Browser sends a request.
File reading is completed.
Database returns data.

Easy Definition:

Event-driven means Node.js performs actions when a specific event occurs.

